The U.S. Agriculture Department isseeking public comments on the question of adjusting theCommodity Credit Corporation's (CCC) discount and premiumschedules to improve the quality of grain it accepts as loancollateral or under price support programs.    The premiums and discounts schedule are based on qualityfactors such as moisture content and kernel damage. Theschedule stipulates the premiums and discounts used for valuinggrain the CCC accepts or purchases during the year.    The department said it is possible that producers could beencouraged to delivery higher quality grain to CCC by adjustingthe premiums and discounts.    Comments are due by April 24 and a report to Congress isrequired by law by May 10. Reuter&#3;